- [x] smarter entrypoint detection, its quite stupid currently. in example when loading a shared library project (mcdope/pam_usb) — verified the concrete complaint against the real `mcdope/pam_usb` repo (fetched over the network): it's a PAM shared library with no `main.c` and no `main()` anywhere in its actual module logic (`pam.c` implements PAM's own `pam_sm_*` callback convention instead), so the old two-stage cascade fell through to the first C-family file with a literal `main()` in tree order — `evdev-helper.c`, a ~65-line setgid helper for one narrow hardware check, picked purely because `-` sorts before `.` alphabetically. Also found, while designing the fix, that every one of that repo's 11 hand-rolled unit-test files (`tests/unit/c/*.c`) has its own `main()` too and is *more* complex than the real source — ruling out "just parse everything and pick whichever main()-having file is most complex" as a fix on its own, since that would pick a test file instead. Fixed with a layered redesign in `main.ts`: every parsable file is first split into a "real source" and "test/spec fixture" bucket (any path segment matching `test`/`tests`/`spec`/`specs`/`__tests__`, case-insensitive — test files are still perfectly normal playable levels later, just never the auto-launched first one); the old C-family-only `main()`-function scan is replaced by a language-agnostic scan-and-score pass (any language's `main`/`Main` function/method entity now counts, catching C#'s capitalized convention too, which the old check never reached) that sums each file's total complexity and keeps the richest main()-having file, falling back to the richest file overall if none had one; each stage (filename convention, then scan-and-score) tries the real-source bucket first and only falls through to the test bucket if that stage found nothing usable, not merely if the bucket was empty; the whole detection pass is capped by a 4s timeout (mirroring the existing highscore-stats timeout pattern) so a 