- [x] canvas should fill as much of the window as possible while keeping aspect ratio — the canvas was capped at `width: min(100%, 960px)`, a fixed max-width that left a lot of a wide monitor unused. Tried a pure-CSS `width:auto; height:auto; max-width:100%; max-height:100%; aspect-ratio:640/400;` fix first and it didn't work: `width:auto` on a replaced element like `<canvas>` falls back to its *intrinsic* size (the 640×400 `width`/`height` attributes) rather than growing to fill available space — `max-width`/`max-height` only ever let it *shrink*, never grow, so the canvas stayed pinned at ~640×400 regardless of window size. Replaced with a JS-driven fit: the canvas is now wrapped in a new `canvasArea` flex-grow `<div>` (absorbs whatever vertical space `#viewport`'s other children — hint caption, controls legend, replay transport bar — don't need) and a `fitCanvasToArea()` function in `main.ts` reads `canvasArea`'s actual content-box size and sets the canvas's inline `width`/`height` in px to the largest 640:400 box that fits inside it, wired up via a `ResizeObserver` on `canvasArea` (fires automatically on window resizes *and* on `canvasArea.hidden` flipping false at a level launch — no explicit call needed at each call site). Also moved `canvas.hidden` toggling to `canvasArea.hidden` throughout (`showLoadingScreen`, `launchLevel`, `showFileTreePlaceholder`, `startReplay`) — hiding an *ancestor* of the Fullscreen API's target element ends fullscreen the same way hiding the element itself does, so this preserves the exact same "leaving the game ends fullscreen, a level transition doesn't" timing the old `canvas.hidden` comment described. `fitCanvasToArea()` is a no-op while `canvas` is actually the fullscreen element (checked via `document.fullscreenElement === canvas`), leaving `.scene-canvas:fullscreen`'s existing CSS to own that state entirely — turned out to be a redundant-but-harmless guard in practice, since the Fullscreen API's UA-level top-layer sizing overrides any inline style regardless, confirmed by direct testing. Verified via Playwright against the real dev server: measured the canvas's actual rendered size at 1920×1080 (1292×808, aspect ratio exactly 1.600 — previously would have capped at 960×600), 1400×900 (772×483), and 1024×700 (396×248) windows, confirmed `canvasArea` genuinely flex-grows via computed-style inspection (not just eyeballing), and confirmed fullscreen enter (fills the full viewport) and exit (cleanly reverts to the fitted size) both still work correctly [Task 59].
- [x] ghidra causes WAY to less dmg - i had to use 2 rockets on some enemies, thats ridicolous considering its a rocket launcher — root cause was purely numeric: a regular (non-pack, non-Elite) enemy's HP scales with its function's complexity (`HP_PER_COMPLEXITY = 25` per point, up to `ELITE_COMPLEXITY_THRESHOLD = 40` before it splits into a pack or becomes an Elite instead), so even a single, unremarkable function with complexity 3-9 already sits at 75-225 HP — routinely above ghidra's old 70 ground-zero `damagePerPellet`, and a direct/near hit rarely even reaches that max once `rocketDamageAt`'s distance falloff is applied. Bumped `damagePerPellet` 70 → 100 (`weapons.ts`), still felt weak in a second playtest pass — bumped again to 150. Blast radius/falloff floor/ammo cost/cooldown all left untouched both times, so this is purely "hits harder," not "hits farther or cheaper" (note: this does mean point-blank self-splash is now more dangerous too, an intentional side effect of the existing "standing too close to your own blast still hurts you" risk/reward design, not a new bug). Verified with `tsc --noEmit`; no other file hardcoded the old damage numbers [Task 60].
- [x] rockets / ghidra pellets should have a nice "boom" particle effect when they hit (be it a wall, or a target) — the existing rocket-blast VFX (`Explosion` in `effects.ts`) was just a growing/fading flat orange ring, no actual debris. Added `ExplosionParticle`: a burst of 16 small squares per detonation that fly outward and up under gravity, cooling in color from a hot white-yellow core through orange to a smoky ember as each one's own remaining life runs out (`spawnExplosionParticles`/`updateExplosionParticles`/`renderExplosionParticles`), layered on top of the existing ring rather than replacing it. Deliberately not gated by the Gore setting (that's specifically about *blood* volume) — a rocket always kicks up the same debris regardless of gore level. Per a same-thread follow-up ask, also gave rockets their own distinct "boom" — `audio.ts` gained `playRocketExplosion()` (a deep sub-bass sweep plus a short filtered white-noise crack transient, bigger/punchier than the existing mine thud) and `advanceRockets` now calls it instead of the shared `playExplosion()`. A second follow-up asked for the same particle-burst treatment on mines too: `traps.ts`'s `updateMines` used to return a bare aggregate damage number, silently swallowing *where* a mine went off — changed to return a `MineDetonation[]` (mirroring `rockets.ts`'s existing `RocketExplosion` shape) so `RaycasterEngine` can spawn the same ring+particle VFX at each mine's exact position, for both the proximity fuse (`applyTrapDamage`) and the gunfire-disarm path (`destroyMine`, including a "safely disarmed at range" shot — it still visibly detonates, just too far to hurt the player). Mines intentionally kept their own existing (smaller, duller) `playExplosion` boom rather than switching to the rocket's new one, since "similar visual effects" was the ask, not "identical to a rocket in every way," and the two already had a deliberately distinct sound identity. `MINE_BLAST_RADIUS` (`traps.ts`) exported so the VFX sizing agrees with the real hitbox, same principle `ROCKET_BLAST_RADIUS` already followed. Verified with a real headless-Chromium harness against the actual bundled code (esbuild + `/snap/bin/chromium --headless=new`, this project's standard recipe for non-parser-layer changes): firing a real rocket down a synthetic corridor into a wall, and walking a synthetic player onto a synthetic mine's fuse radius, both produced non-empty `explosions`/`explosionParticles` arrays that correctly aged back out to empty, and the mine correctly went from `alive: true` to `false` — 9/9 assertions passed [Task 61].

- [x] automap not really useful, should work like in diablo instead. rendering is also weird / wasting space — root cause of the "wasted space" look: `GameMap` is always square (mapGenerator's `mapSize()`, 64-160 tiles), but the canvas is a fixed 640×400 landscape surface; the old "shrink the whole grid to fit a box" sizing always let the height budget win, letterboxing the map as a ≤320×320px square with dead scrim on both sides, and shrinking to ~2px/tile on large maps. Reworked to a Diablo-style non-blocking overlay: opening it (Tab) in `engine.ts` no longer early-returns/freezes the sim — movement, combat, enemy AI, hazards, and projectiles all keep running while it's up, with only the purely-visual weapon viewmodel/crosshair/corner-minimap/compass suppressed (the bottom HUD bar now correctly stays visible too, which the old freeze-based path silently dropped). `automap.ts` replaced the shrink-to-fit math with a fixed 10px/tile viewport that uses nearly the full canvas (reserving the bottom HUD strip and a small margin) and pans/clamps to keep the player centered, exactly like Diablo's map — falling back to centering the whole map only when it's smaller than the viewport. Also restyled to a muted greyscale palette (walls/floor/doors/teleporters/secret walls/lore terminals) per explicit follow-up request ("prefer greyscale like in diablo... shouldn't be in the way visually"), keeping small colored accents only on hazards/active spike traps/mines/the exit so danger/goal tiles still read at a glance; the corner minimap's existing accent hues were reused for consistency. `hud.ts`'s `HUD_HEIGHT` constant exported so the automap can reserve the exact same strip. Verified against the real dev server via Playwright: loaded `mcdope/codeenstein3d` (a real 160×160 grid), opened the automap, walked (W) and turned (D) with it open and confirmed via screenshots that the player kept moving/rotating and the camera panned to reveal newly-explored grey tiles while staying centered on the marker, the HUD bar remained visible throughout, and the map now spans the full canvas width instead of a letterboxed square.
