- [x] hash in highscores should be about the workspace, not the current file - this prevents proper comparing — root cause: `HighscoreEntry.hash` (`recordRunHighscore` in `main.ts`) was `hashRun(JSON.stringify(parsed), campaignName())` where `parsed` is only the single file the run happened to end on (died on, or last cleared) — so two runs over the exact same, unedited workspace that merely ended on different levels got unrelated hashes and looked like "different code" in the Highscore UI, defeating the hash's whole purpose. Fixed by folding the hash into the existing whole-codebase background aggregation (`computeCodebaseStats`, already walking every parsable file via `flattenParsableFiles` to sum lines/complexity): each file's path-prefixed parsed-AST JSON is collected in the same stable depth-first order and NUL-joined, then hashed once via `hashRun` alongside the campaign name — `CodebaseStats` gained a `hash` field, and `recordRunHighscore` now prefers `codebaseStats.hash`, only falling back to the old single-file hash if the background aggregation (or `kickOffCodebaseStats`'s own catch path, which now also produces a hash) genuinely didn't finish within `recordRunHighscore`'s bounded wait. The per-level `astHash` used for replay-integrity verification (`replay.ts`'s `ReplayLevelSegment`) is a deliberately separate, still file-scoped mechanism and was left untouched. Updated `doc/user/privacy.md` and `doc/user/hud-and-ui.md` to describe the hash as workspace-wide rather than per-level. Verified with `tsc --noEmit` [Task 64].
- [x] broaden secret rooms causes for looting — dead code (unreachable statements after a `return`) was the only AST pattern that ever triggered a secret room, too rare a find in clean, well-tested codebases. `ParsedFile.deadCodeRegions` generalized into `ParsedFile.secretTriggers: SecretTrigger[]` (a `kind` tag plus start/end line), fed by four new detectors in `astUtils.ts` alongside the existing dead-code one: `findEmptyCatchBlocks` (a catch/except/rescue whose body is empty or contains only comments — a swallowed exception), `findDeprecationMarkers` (`@deprecated`, `[Obsolete]`, or a bare "deprecated" found in a comment, decorator/annotation/attribute node, or string literal — the last one deliberately included so Python-style triple-quoted docstrings are caught too, at the minor cost of a stray runtime string mentioning "deprecated" also counting), `findCommentedOutCodeBlocks` (contiguous comment-node runs, merged across adjacent lines since stacked `//` lines are separate sibling nodes, that span more than 6 lines or contain `{`/`}`/`;`), and `findMagicNumberBlobs` (string literals over 100 chars with no whitespace — Base64/hash-shaped — or a well-known hex magic number: `0xDEADBEEF`, `0xCAFEBABE`, `0x1337`, `0xC0FFEE`, `0xBAADF00D`, `0xDEADC0DE`, `0x8BADF00D`, `0xFEEDFACE`). Node-type vocabulary for catch/annotation/string/number literals added to the shared generic-adapter table (`vocabulary.ts`, covering all 13 generic languages) and as small local constants in the PHP/C bespoke adapters, matching each's existing per-adapter node-type-list pattern; C skips empty-catch detection entirely (the grammar has no exceptions) and scans only comments for deprecation markers (no decorator/attribute concept in scope). `placeSecretRooms` (`mapGenerator.ts`) now shuffles the combined trigger list before applying its existing 5-per-level cap, so the five pattern kinds sample fairly instead of whichever kind happens to be concatenated first (dead code) silently hogging every slot in a file that has several. Also addressed a same-thread follow-up ask: the level-start briefing now shows a "Secrets" stat (`GameMap.secretRoomCount`, threaded through `LevelStartInfo`) alongside Rooms/Enemies, so the player knows up front whether it's worth watching the walls. `doc/user/mechanics.md`, `doc/dev/game-design.md`, and the `index.html` intro screen's "How it works" mapping updated to describe the broadened trigger set; `consoleSidebar.ts` gained a matching flavor hint. Verified with `tsc --noEmit` [Task 65]. Follow-up: playtesting surfaced three real bugs from the broadened trigger set, all fixed. (1) A secret wall next to a lore terminal always triggered the terminal instead — the interact handler (`engine.ts`) checked lore-terminal proximity first (any terminal within `LORE_INTERACT_RADIUS = 1.8` tiles, any direction) and unconditionally returned before ever reaching `tryOpenSecretWall()`'s much tighter facing-based `SECRET_WALL_REACH = 0.9` check; flipped the order so the more deliberate facing-based secret-wall check runs first, falling back to the lore terminal only when it doesn't hit one — `tryOpenSecretWall()` now returns whether it actually opened something. (2) A single file produced 5 secret rooms all carved off the same anchor room — `placeSecretRooms` had no memory of which anchor rooms it had already used, so nothing stopped several different trigger kinds resolving to the same room (or even the same trigger's anchor) from each independently succeeding on a different side of that one room; added a `usedAnchors` set capping it at one secret room per room, walking the full shuffled trigger list (not just the first 5) until the level-wide cap is filled or triggers run out. Fixing that surfaced a deeper, pre-existing root cause shared with lore terminals and goto teleporters: `roomForLine` returned the *first* room whose entity line-range contained a trigger's line, but a method's range always sits inside its enclosing class's range too — since classes always sort before their own methods by `startLine`, every trigger physically inside *any* method of a class was silently anchoring to the whole class's room instead of that method's own room. Fixed `roomForLine` to pick the containing room with the smallest line span (the innermost/most specific entity) instead of the first match — benefits lore terminal and teleporter placement the same way, not just secret rooms. (3) Every secret room seen so far only ever contained health, never rockets — confirmed with the user this was simply because the rocket launcher (ghidra) wasn't unlocked yet on that run, which makes it always health by design (`hasRocketLauncher && rng() < 0.5 ? "rockets" : "health"`, the same ownership gate every other rocket-ammo source in the game already uses) — not a bug, no code change. All three verified against the real running `RaycasterEngine`/`MapGenerator`/parser code in headless Chromium (a stubbed `InputSource` driving real `advance(dt)` calls to confirm interact-priority; synthetic multi-pattern-in-one-function and multi-method-in-one-class PHP sources through the real parser+generator to confirm one-room-max and correct per-method anchoring) and against the real app via Playwright (GitHub-loaded `mcdope/codeenstein3d`, Secrets count rose from 3 to 5 once methods stopped collapsing into their class's room). Second follow-up: (3) turned out to actually need a fix after all — the underlying two-way `hasRocketLauncher ? coinflip(rockets, health) : health` table meant any player who hadn't unlocked ghidra yet really would see *only* health, run after run, with no other outcome ever possible; per explicit ask, secret-room loot needed a real chance at a weapon unlock and an armor drop too, since "if they only spawn health all the time there is no point in searching them." Reworked `placeSecretRooms`'s loot roll into a uniform pick among whatever's actually available that run: health and armor (`"swap"`, `SECRET_LOOT_SWAP_AMOUNT = 40`) are always candidates, rockets joins once the launcher's owned, and a still-unowned gdb/ghidra joins as a `"weapon"` candidate once at least one exists — so armor alone already breaks the "always health" complaint regardless of weapon/rocket state, and finding a secret room can now hand you a weapon outright instead of just ammo/health. `AmmoPickup` (`map/types.ts`) gained a `"weapon"` kind and an optional `weaponIndex` field (mirroring `LootDrop`'s existing shape); `RaycasterEngine.collectLoot()`'s static-pickup path gained a `"weapon"` case, and the already-owned-weapon-tops-up-ammo-instead-of-wasting-the-drop logic (previously only in `applyLoot`, for enemy-kill drops) was factored out into a new shared `grantOrTopUpWeapon()` used by both paths, so a secret-room weapon drop that turns out to already be owned (e.g. a second secret room rolling the same still-missing weapon, or the player unlocking it mid-level via an Elite kill first) gracefully falls back to an elite-sized ammo top-up instead of doing nothing. `UNLOCKABLE_WEAPONS` moved from a private `engine.ts` constant to `weapons.ts` (exported) so `main.ts` can compute a `missingWeaponIndices` list from `ownedWeapons` and hand it down through `MapGenerator.generate()` to `placeSecretRooms` as an opaque `number[]` — the map layer never imports engine-layer weapon concepts (a hard architecture rule, see `doc/dev/architecture.md`), same reasoning `hasRocketLauncher` already followed. Both `main.ts` call sites (live level launch and replay playback) updated identically, threading it from the correct source (`carryover`/`segment.carryover`) for each so replay determinism isn't disturbed — same care `hasRocketLauncher` already required. Loot-billboard rendering needed no changes at all: `collectLootBillboards` was already structurally typed against `LootDrop["kind"]` rather than `LootDrop` itself, so a secret room's `"weapon"` pickup automatically gets the same pulsing violet ring as an Elite's weapon drop. `doc/user/mechanics.md`/`doc/dev/game-design.md` updated to describe the new loot table. Verified against the real code in headless Chromium (60+ seeds confirmed health/swap/rockets/weapon all actually occur — not just theoretically possible — plus every `"weapon"` entry carries a valid index and the gated-off case correctly never produces rockets/weapon; a real `RaycasterEngine.advance()` pass confirmed walking onto a `"weapon"` pickup grants and auto-equips it, and a second pass confirmed an already-owned one tops up gdb's smg ammo pool instead) and via Playwright against the real app (no console errors). Third follow-up, per explicit request: both the always-on corner minimap (`renderMinimap` in `raycaster.ts`) and the Tab automap (`drawAutomap` in `automap.ts`) rendered an unopened secret wall in its own subtly-distinct color from a plain wall — a real, if small, giveaway of exactly where every secret room was, defeating the whole "find it yourself" point; the corner minimap's version was worse, since (unlike the automap) it has no fog-of-war gate at all and drew every secret wall's tinted position from the moment a level loaded, before the player had gone anywhere. Both now render `SECRET_WALL_TILE` with the exact same fill as a plain wall — merged into the same branch/color pass rather than a separate one — so an unopened secret wall is genuinely indistinguishable from a real one on either map; once opened it's just plain floor (tile `0`) and needed no special handling at all. The automap's now-unused `SECRET_WALL_COLOR` constant was removed. The one remaining, intentional discovery hint is the much subtler in-view tint (`secretWallTint` in `raycaster.ts`'s 3D wall-cast, a separate code path, untouched) — "very slightly tinted if you look closely," per `doc/user/mechanics.md`. `doc/user/hud-and-ui.md`'s automap description (which had explicitly documented the leak as a feature) corrected to match. Verified by directly calling the real `renderMinimap`/`drawAutomap` against a synthetic map with both a plain and an unopened secret wall and sampling the actual rendered canvas pixels (`ctx.getImageData`): the two tiles' pixels are now byte-identical, the old distinct secret-wall colors (`#424a5f`/`#377fb8` minimap, `#c2c2c8` automap) no longer appear anywhere in either render at all, and an opened secret wall (tile reset to `0`) renders identically to ordinary explored floor. Fourth follow-up: the previous fix only hid the *passage* — the room's interior itself, carved to plain floor (`0`) at generation time in `trySecretRoomOffAnchor`, was still a giveaway: since the corner minimap has no fog-of-war at all and only ever draws wall-colored pixels (floor is simply never painted, left as the translucent panel background), a 3×3 patch of floor sitting inside a sea of solid rock showed up as an obvious room-shaped *hole*, from the moment the level loaded, regardless of the door tile's own color now matching. The automap leaked the same shape too, via a different path: `markVisited`'s reveal radius (`VISITED_REVEAL_RADIUS = 5`, no wall/line-of-sight awareness at all) easily reaches 1-2 tiles past an unopened door from the anchor room's own floor, marking the interior `visited` and letting it fall through to the automap's plain-floor color well before the door is ever opened. Root-caused and fixed properly rather than patched around: `trySecretRoomOffAnchor` now carves the *entire* room footprint — interior and the one connecting tile alike — as `SECRET_WALL_TILE`, not floor; since every render path already treats `SECRET_WALL_TILE` as an ordinary wall (from the prior two follow-ups), a room made entirely of it is genuinely indistinguishable from solid rock on any map, unconditionally, with no fog-of-war or visited-radius edge case left to leak through. `tryOpenSecretWall()` (`engine.ts`) now flood-fills the whole connected 4-directional `SECRET_WALL_TILE` component from the tile opened, converting it all to floor at once, instead of only the single tile the player interacted with — opening the door reveals the whole room in one beat, as it visually always appeared to. Also hardened the room-placement "clear" check with a 1-tile margin around the footprint (not just the footprint itself) before carving, so two different secret rooms can never end up 4-connected/touching — without it, the new flood-fill-on-open could otherwise leak from one room into a second, unrelated one if their footprints ever happened to abut. Confirmed harmless to existing pathfinding/collision/scoring: `SECRET_WALL_TILE` was already treated as solid/impassable everywhere (player collision, enemy AI, `shortestPath`'s BFS) identically to plain wall, and the sole *walkable-tile* consequence is that the "100% Clear" score bonus's denominator now actually excludes secret-room interiors as `isWalkableTile`'s own doc comment already (inaccurately, until now) claimed — previously only the single door tile was excluded, with the interior silently counted despite being unreachable before opening. Verified against the real parser+`MapGenerator`+`RaycasterEngine` in headless Chromium: flood-filled every `SECRET_WALL_TILE` component on a real generated map and confirmed the component count matches `secretRoomCount` with no undersized (1-tile) or merged components; rendered the real minimap and confirmed every tile of every secret room's footprint (not just the door) pixel-matches plain wall exactly; and drove a real engine interact through a real secret door, confirming the *entire* connected 10-tile room flips to floor in one action, not just the tile faced.
