- [x] flamethrower playtest: range too high, a flamethrower is a closecombat weapon - guess that mean like 1 to 3 tiles, needs testing. firing animation looks like bullet shots, should look more like an actual firing flamethrower instead. if possible: add a burning particle fx to hit enemies as well (no DoT though, it hits hard enough already) — Task 67's cone-spread-only "reads as short range" bet didn't hold up in practice: the Cone of Fire's random deviation still let pellets connect well past a real flamethrower's reach. Added a new `Weapon.maxRange` field (`weapons.ts`, ranged-only counterpart to the existing melee-only `meleeRange`) and set it to 2.5 tiles (later bumped to 3.5, see follow-up below) for Friday Hotfix — `fire()` now gates a hitscan hit (both enemies and mines) behind `weapon.meleeRange ?? weapon.maxRange`, a genuine hard cutoff layered on top of the spread instead of relying on it alone. Replaced the per-pellet thin bullet-tracer line Friday Hotfix shared with every other hitscan gun with a dedicated `FlameStream` effect (`effects.ts`): one fanning, flickering two-layer wedge per shot (spanning the widest/narrowest column any of that shot's pellets actually landed on) instead of 6 separate straight lines, re-jittered every frame so a held trigger reads as a roaring flame rather than a static shape or a spray of bullets. Added `spawnBurnParticles` (`effects.ts`): a handful of small, short-lived embers reusing the existing rocket-detonation `ExplosionParticle` type/update/render pipeline (same cooling white→orange→ember palette, just far fewer/slower/shorter than a full detonation burst, since Friday Hotfix can land several hits a second), spawned from `damageEnemy()` only when the hit came from the `"gas"` ammo pool — purely cosmetic, no damage-over-time added. Verified with a headless-Chromium harness (this project's standard non-parser-layer recipe) driving the real bundled `RaycasterEngine.fire()` against a synthetic map: a point-blank (1 tile) shot damages the target, a 6-tile shot (past the new 2.5-tile `maxRange`) does not, a gas shot pushes exactly one `FlameStream` and zero per-pellet bullet traces, a connecting gas hit spawns burn particles, and a plain pistol shot still pushes its ordinary bullet trace (regression check) — 7/7 assertions passed [Task 68]. Follow-up: two more playtest notes on the same feature. (1) The cone was still too wide and flared immediately off the nozzle instead of only widening near the end — narrowed `spreadPx` 100 → 45 (now tighter than the shotgun's 70px; the hard `maxRange` does the actual range-limiting work now, not a wide cone) and reworked `FlameStream`'s rendering (`effects.ts`) from a straight-sided wedge to a `flameJet` shape whose edges follow a `t^power` curve instead of a straight line — needle-thin for most of the distance, only actually fanning out in the last stretch before the tip, with the brighter inner core layer using a higher power so it stays narrower still. (2) The burn-hit particle effect was barely noticeable — root cause was reusing `ExplosionParticle`'s "burn out mid-air, never settle" physics, sized for a rocket's instant flash rather than a lingering ember; added a dedicated `BurnParticle` type/pipeline (`spawnBurnParticles`/`updateBurnParticles`/`renderBurnParticles`) that falls under gravity like debris but then settles and glows for `BURN_SETTLED_LIFE` (1.6s) once landed, the same "fall, then linger" shape as `BloodParticle`'s floor stain. Hit a real bug while tuning this: the airborne `life` value (originally 0.3-0.5s) could expire before the particle physically reached the floor (worst case ~0.8s given its gravity/velocity ranges), deleting the ember mid-fall before it ever got to settle and linger — fixed by not aging airborne particles out at all; `life` only starts counting down once `settled` flips true. Verified with an extended headless-Chromium harness: `spreadPx` confirmed narrower than the shotgun's; a pixel-sampled canvas check of the real `drawFlameStreams` output confirms the jet stays unfilled off-center halfway up its length but is filled both dead-center there and out at the edge near the tip (the narrow-then-flare shape, not a straight wedge); a real gas hit's ember is confirmed still alive a full second later (proof it settled and is lingering, not blinking out) and confirmed gone by 3 seconds (proof it isn't permanent either) — all assertions passed on the first run after the airborne-life fix. Second follow-up: `maxRange` bumped one tile further, 2.5 → 3.5 (`weapons.ts`) — the short-range identity itself wasn't in question, just felt a notch too tight in practice.
- [x] ensure engine is paused when canvas is not focussed — the existing pause-on-blur only fired on the whole *window* losing focus (alt-tab). It never checked whether the canvas itself was the focused element, so `InputController`'s keydown/keyup listeners (bound to `window`) still fired while, say, the GitHub-repo sidebar text field had focus: typing there sent WASD/Space/Tab/etc. straight into the game (moving the player, firing, toggling the automap) and even blocked the letters themselves from being typed, since `preventDefault()` ran unconditionally for movement keys/Space/Tab. Moved the gameplay keydown/keyup listeners from `window` to the canvas element itself (`input.ts`), so they now only ever fire while the canvas is the actually-focused DOM element; added a `blur` listener on the canvas (alongside the existing `window` one) that forces the same pause-and-clear-keys path as an alt-tab, so losing focus to any other on-page control now pauses the game exactly like it already did for losing focus to another app. `onCanvasClick` now also explicitly calls `canvas.focus()` for browsers (Safari) that don't auto-focus a clicked non-text element. Verified against the real dev server via Playwright: with the canvas focused, W visibly advances the minimap marker; clicking into the GitHub repo text field pauses the game (the existing "PAUSED / Click to resume, or press Esc again" overlay appears) and typing "wasd test" (including the space) lands correctly in the field instead of moving/firing/toggling the automap; merely refocusing the canvas (without a real click) correctly leaves it paused, matching the pre-existing click/Escape-to-resume design rather than silently un-pausing on focus alone. Follow-up: the canvas-blur-forces-pause half of this fix introduced a real regression — pressing Escape while playing (pointer-locked) stopped pausing the game at all. Root cause: real browsers (headless Chromium doesn't reproduce this, which is why the earlier verification missed it) also release pointer lock as a mandatory side effect of Escape while locked, and that release blurs the canvas a moment later, either just before or just after the Escape keydown itself is processed depending on timing; `RaycasterEngine.advance()` drains blur and Escape in the same frame (`if (consumeBlur()) isPaused = true; if (consumeEscape()) isPaused = !isPaused;`), so the blur-forced pause and Escape's own toggle collided and canceled each other out regardless of which order they landed in. A first attempt at fixing this with a timing-window guard in `input.ts` (suppress the canvas-blur pause if it followed an Escape press within ~100ms) only covered the escape-then-blur ordering and still broke on the reverse — a real browser can blur the canvas *before* the Escape keydown is even dispatched to the page at all, meaning a canvas-scoped keydown listener could miss the event entirely. Replaced both attempts with two changes: (1) Escape's own keydown handling moved out of the canvas-scoped listener into a dedicated `window`-level one (`onWindowEscape`, `input.ts`) — the same reasoning `GameHud`'s own overlay-dismiss listener already uses window-scoping for — so it's guaranteed to fire regardless of where DOM focus actually lands; (2) `RaycasterEngine.advance()` now resolves Escape as authoritative over a same-frame blur instead of two independent writes (`if (escaped) isPaused = !isPaused; else if (blurred) isPaused = true;`), so Escape always wins regardless of which order the two fired in within that frame, and the input-layer timing-guess machinery could be deleted entirely. Verified in headless Chromium by manually dispatching both race orderings (Escape-then-blur and blur-then-Escape) directly on `window`/the canvas — both now resolve to a correct pause from a genuinely-running state — and reconfirmed plain Escape toggling, sidebar-click-forces-pause, and typing into the sidebar text field all still work exactly as before. Second follow-up: still didn't actually fix it — the user confirmed live that Escape while playing only released the mouse lock and never paused. The real root cause was more fundamental than a race: real browsers deliberately do NOT dispatch a `keydown` event at all for the specific Escape press that exits pointer lock — a documented Pointer Lock API security measure (so a page can never detect or interfere with the user's own escape hatch) — meaning `onWindowEscape` never sees that keypress no matter where it's bound. Headless Chromium never surfaced this because it doesn't implement real pointer-lock release on Escape either (confirmed: `document.pointerLockElement` stayed the canvas after a synthesized Escape press throughout every earlier "verification," which is why all of that testing was blind to the actual bug). Fixed by detecting the *loss of pointer lock itself* instead of trying to catch the keypress that causes it: added a `pointerlockchange` listener (`onPointerLockChange`, `input.ts`) that queues a new edge-triggered `pointerUnlockQueued` signal whenever `document.pointerLockElement` stops being the canvas — this is the only reliable channel left, and it doesn't care what caused the unlock (Escape being the common case, but it's correct for any cause). Threaded a matching `consumePointerUnlock()` through `InputSource`/`InputController`/`ReplayPlaybackInput` and a `pointerUnlock` field through `InputSnapshot` (`input.ts`, `replay.ts`) so replay recording/playback stays byte-faithful. `RaycasterEngine.advance()` now forces a pause on `blurred || pointerUnlocked`, with Escape's own toggle still taking priority if a real keydown *also* lands in the same frame (kept from the previous fix, since some browsers/situations may not suppress it). Verified in headless Chromium by forcing the exact real-browser signal directly — overriding `document.pointerLockElement` to `null` and dispatching a bare `pointerlockchange` event with *no* accompanying keydown at all — and confirmed the pause now fires correctly from that alone; also reconfirmed plain Escape (pointer not locked), sidebar-click-forces-pause + text field typing, resuming via click, and a keydown+pointerlockchange landing together (still resolves to Escape-wins) all still behave correctly [Task 69]
- [x] keys part of a ongoing cheat input sequence shouldnt be interpreted as input. if input started with "I", ignore following keys for controls if they could be part of a cheat. else interupt the cheat detection sequence and treat it as normal input — `InputController.onKeyDown` (`src/engine/input.ts`) now checks the cheat-prefix match *before* any control branch: a letter that keeps `cheatBuffer` a valid prefix of `IDDQD`/`IDKFA`/`IDCLIP` is swallowed entirely (never added to the held-keys set, never triggers R/F/etc.) and returns early, so typing e.g. "IDDQD" can no longer also strafe (D) or turn (Q) the player via those overlapping letters. The instant a typed letter stops extending every prefix, the buffer resets to empty and that letter (and anything typed after it) falls through to normal control handling again, exactly as before. Replaced the old design (a non-blocking rolling suffix-match buffer that let every cheat letter double as a live control) — `CHEAT_BUFFER_MAX`/slicing removed since the buffer is now naturally capped by the longest code's length. Verified in headless Chromium (bundled `input.ts` standalone via esbuild, dispatched real `KeyboardEvent`s at a canvas): typing "IDDQD" now leaves `KeyD`/`KeyQ` unheld while still firing the cheat; an interrupted sequence ("I" then "W", not a valid continuation) correctly drops the buffer and lets "W" register as normal held movement; a fresh valid sequence typed right after an interruption still fires correctly; and plain WASD with no relation to any cheat is completely unaffected [Task 70]
- [x] still annoyingly long corridors at times. if we cant solve it with geometry, add random rooms and enemies (called "edge case", visually different from other enemies and smaller) there to break the "endless walk feeling". best would be: shorter coridors AND that breakup mechanism — did both halves, per the note. Geometry half: `mapGenerator.ts` gained `MAX_CORRIDOR_STRAIGHT_LENGTH = 9`; a new post-carve pass (`breakUpLongCorridors`, run right after `connectRooms`) scans the fully-carved grid for straight runs past that length — necessary because run length is a property of the whole grid, not any single carved leg, since two unrelated corridor legs can land collinear and combine into one long run neither leg alone exceeds. Each run is interrupted by injecting a small 3x3/4x4 walkable "breakup room" into the path (`tryInjectBreakupRoom`), falling back to forcing a 90° jog (sever a short choke-point stretch back to wall, reroute 2-3 tiles around it) when a room would collide with existing geometry (`tryForceJog`) — a primary pass splits each run into evenly-spaced segments in one shot (cheap, well-distributed), with a small bounded set of wide-search safety-net rescans mopping up anything left over (two legs landing collinear, or a couple of adjacent evenly-spaced targets both landing in the same locally-blocked spot). Breakup rooms are tracked as a new `GameMap.breakupRooms: Rect[]`, deliberately kept separate from the AST-derived `Room[]` array (no synthetic `CodeEntity` needed) so every existing kind-gated system (enemy spawning, hazards, doors, secret rooms, pillars, ...) is structurally blind to them with zero changes — only `placeKeys`/`placeTraps`, which scan the whole grid rather than iterating `rooms`, needed an explicit exclusion. Gameplay half: every breakup room gets 1-3 new "Edge Case" enemies (`spawnEdgeCaseEnemies`, modeled on the existing TODO/FIXME "Bug" encounter's synthetic-`CodeEntity` pattern) — small (0.55x sprite scale), jarring cyan-tinted (`#00FFFF`, `sprites.ts`), 10-15 HP, ~2.2x normal move speed, erratic darting roam (random early retargeting + a per-step heading wobble instead of a smooth glide, `enemyAi.ts`), and ~0.4x normal melee/ranged damage — a literal "bug in the system." Still runs through the exact same aggro/line-of-sight/chase state machine as every other enemy (`Enemy.edgeCase`, mirroring the existing `elite` flag), just with different speed/damage constants. Verified against the real generator/AI/sprite code: a Node+esbuild harness confirmed deterministic regeneration from the same seed, structural exclusivity in both directions (no normal enemy ever spawns in a breakup room, no Edge Case enemy ever spawns outside one), and correct HP (10-15)/per-room count (1-3) ranges; a real headless-Chromium canvas pixel-sample confirmed the correct cyan tint and ~0.55x projected size vs. a normal enemy at the same distance. Caveat found while stress-testing with unusually large/dense synthetic files (30-45 entities on a maxed-out 160-tile map): `connectRooms` chains rooms by parse order, not proximity, so some individual corridor legs are already extremely long by construction (one synthetic case had a 93-tile unbroken run) — the breakup pass reliably brings ordinary/moderate-sized files fully under the limit and dramatically shortens even the worst adversarial cases (that 93-tile run reduced to 13), but doesn't mathematically guarantee zero over-limit runs in every extreme case, matching this generator's existing "best-effort, never a hard failure" placement convention used throughout the file (see `placeTraps`'s doc comment) [Task 72]. Follow-up: playtest feedback that breakup rooms always looked like the same square and the corridor ran straight through them uninterrupted, both correctly diagnosed as real gaps in the first pass. `tryInjectBreakupRoom` now rolls its along-run and across-run dimensions independently (3-5 tiles each, not always a forced 3x3/4x4 square) and offsets the run's own line off-center across the room's width instead of always dead-centering it, so consecutive rooms actually look different from each other. More importantly, a new `breakUpRoomSightline` walls off one interior column/row of the room with a single guaranteed 1-tile gap positioned away from the entry/exit line (the same "solid wall, one gap" technique `carveLabyrinth`'s `divide` already uses for guaranteed connectivity) — without it, the room was just a wider stretch of the same straight corridor, since flooding a rect on top of an already-carved straight run does nothing to interrupt the sightline still running directly through its middle. Hit a real, systematic bug while verifying this: `enemyPositions`' first-enemy-at-room-center pick frequently landed exactly on the new baffle tile for these small odd-dimensioned rooms, and `clearCriticalTiles` (which force-clears the tile under every enemy's position to guarantee it's floor) then silently punched the baffle back open — in a first verification pass this defeated the sightline fix on the majority of rooms, not a rare edge case. Fixed with a new `nearestFloorInRect` that snaps any Edge Case enemy spawn position landing on a wall tile to the nearest actual floor tile within its room (BFS-bounded to the room's own footprint) before `clearCriticalTiles` ever sees it. Verified against the real generator: a Node+esbuild harness confirmed real shape variety (9+ distinct width×height combinations) and, across repeated seeds on small/typical/medium-sized synthetic files, the intended entry-exit sightline is broken in every room checked (0 failures) — a residual ~15% "still straight" rate persists only in an artificially dense worst-case stress scenario (30+ entities packed onto a maxed-out map), traced to coincidental adjacency from a *different*, unrelated corridor touching the room's other wall (a pre-existing property of this generator's parse-order-chained corridor connectivity, not a failure of the baffle itself, which the room's own entry/exit line was confirmed broken in every case checked)

- [x] remove compass feature flag, not needed anymore — the exit compass had been stable and enabled since Task 39's redesign, so the `COMPASS_ENABLED` gate (`hud.ts`) was dead weight; removed the constant and its doc comment and inlined `drawCompass`'s call in `engine.ts` unconditionally (dropped the `if` and the now-unused import). No behavior change — the flag was already `true`. Verified with `tsc --noEmit` [Task 73]
- [x] fps counter shows 60fps with <17ms frametime when paused, is the engine really paused when the game is paused? — investigated, not a bug: `advance()` (`engine.ts`) genuinely early-returns while `isPaused` is true, right after drawing the paused overlay, so no movement/AI/physics/combat runs. What's still ticking is the render loop itself — `frame()` calls `updateFpsCounter(rawDt)` unconditionally every `requestAnimationFrame` tick, *before* `advance()`'s pause check, deliberately using the raw unclamped delta (see its own comment) so the overlay reflects true frame cadence rather than being floored by `MAX_DT` clamping; `renderPausedOverlay()` also does real per-frame work (redraws the frozen scene + pause overlay), so the browser keeps firing rAF at its normal refresh rate throughout. The counter was always measuring render-loop cadence, not simulation activity, so ~60fps/<17ms while paused is expected. No code change made.
